This article is part of my SOLID Principles in Angular series, where I break down each SOLID principle from an Angular engineer’s perspective using practical examples and real-world Angular scenarios.
In this article, we’ll focus on the Interface Segregation Principle (ISP).
Like the other SOLID principles, this one is simple to understand in theory, but applying it consistently in real-world applications requires experience and thoughtful design.
When used correctly, ISP helps us build Angular applications that are easier to maintain, scale, and evolve as business requirements grow. It’s time to break it down and see how it applies to modern Angular development.
What does the Interface Segregation Principle say?
Clients should not depend on interfaces they don’t use.
Bad example:
interface Worker {
code(): void;
test(): void;
deploy(): void;
}Problem? Not every worker performs all these tasks. For example:

• Developers may code

• QA engineers may test

• DevOps engineers may deploy
This interface forces unnecessary dependencies, which lead us to bad design.
Better:
interface Developer {
code(): void;
}interface Tester {
test(): void;
}As you noticed, Smaller interfaces are usually better because they are easier to understand and easier to maintain.
ISP in Angular
Interface Segregation becomes very important in Angular applications as projects grow. In theory, everyone agrees that small, focused interfaces are better, but in real projects, I often see Angular codebases full of oversized interfaces. A common example is state management.
interface AppState {
currentUser: User | null;
users: User[];
products: Product[];
cartItems: CartItem[];
selectedProduct: Product | null;
authToken: string | null;
permissions: string[];
orders: Order[];
notifications: Notification[];
}At first, this may seem convenient because everything is in one place, but as the application grows, this becomes painful. Why? Because now unrelated features depend on a giant shared interface.
For example:

• Authentication only needs auth-related data

• Product pages only need the product state

• The Cart feature only needs cart data
Yet everything depends on the same large structure, which creates unnecessary coupling. A better approach is to split the state by feature.
interface AuthState {
currentUser: User | null;
authToken: string | null;
permissions: string[];
}interface ProductState {
products: Product[];
selectedProduct: Product | null;
}
interface CartState {
cartItems: CartItem[];
}
This design is much cleaner, and its benefits are:

• better separation of concerns

• easier maintenance

• easier scaling

• lower coupling
ISP also applies to services.
Bad example:
interface UserOperations {
getUsers(): void;
createUser(): void;
deleteUser(): void;
exportUsers(): void;
sendEmail(): void;
}Not every consumer needs all these operations. A component that only displays users should not depend on export or email functionality. Smaller contracts usually lead to better architecture. This is one of those principles that becomes more valuable as Angular applications scale
That’s it for this article. I hope this gave you a practical understanding of how the Interface Segregation Principle applies to real-world Angular development. In the next article, we’ll continue the series by exploring the Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP) in Angular and see how it influences Angular architecture.
Thanks for reading, and I’ll see you in the next one.
